data.text: Yesterday we did a lot of data collection and can now read information we pull from the JSON file.

The program is in confirmed working order and is planned to be used to be an interactive writing system for our autonomous drive commands.  It's possible that this project could go back to development to include recording other actions.

card.name: Create a movement recording LinearOpMode
card.desc: This is an opMode built to letting a user drive a robot, and the users actions get recorded and converted back into a runnable file with editable inputs in case of future changes.

data.text: Created most of the data collection for JSON files and was able to read the records of the trello boards.

Today, the formula was discovered to have the incorrect input being fed in, and after re-evaluating the process needed to back drive the distance driven, the function inputs were corrected.  Now, the program is moving to a point to be tested with normal drive and turn functions implemented to provide a sense to the accuracy of the recorder.

[general distance to encoder fomula.gif](https://trello-attachments.s3.amazonaws.com/5b71beda9b895f312b9bf867/5b9405f9494f112a6426e5eb/b60cc0a98357ff6cabcc138ec648435f/general_distance_to_encoder_fomula.gif) [general distance to encoder fomula.gif](https://trello-attachments.s3.amazonaws.com/5b71beda9b895f312b9bf867/5b9405f9494f112a6426e5eb/b60cc0a98357ff6cabcc138ec648435f/general_distance_to_encoder_fomula.gif) 

This is the normal formula used to convert a distance to encoder counts.  To create the back driving formula, we started with encoder counts and ran the formula backwards to the input matching the recorded movement.

Today, I worked on resolving a motor speed difference issue that has been causing our motors to stop at different times from each other due to not running the correct speeds. It seems that the motor mode has some effect on this, as when in RUN_WITHOUT_ENCODERS the robot will drift one way, while in RUN_WITH_ENCODERS or RUN_TO_POSITION results in the robot drifting the other way. I was unable to resolve this issue today.
We wrote out a possible outlook for our final product. We discussed the structure and format of our program.
Began the first test on parsing the JSON file. Eventually, we were able to gather information using JSON keys. 9/16

The control lock error was fixed, and both motors were fixed (They originally didn't exit Reset Encoder mode).  However, the formulas needed revision, as the movements recorded didn't match the expected distances traveled.  Corrections coming soon.
A logic error in the control lock for the controller caused one one motor to move and the control lock to not function.
Created a repository for the JSON project in order to cooperate more effiectly
We created a repository and began to place files in it.

(Last meeting) While attempting to import a JSON library into eclipse and failing. We tried to import the library though Maven, a tool in java that addresses two aspects of building software like how software is built, and its dependencies.
Last meeting (9/11/18) we learned what Maven is and how to use it. We also got the JSON file from Trello and began to take a look at it and the process to parse JSON to Java.
After some basic logic organization today, a compiler error was hit and progress was halted until the project could be reverted for the next meeting.
